ce:section.ce:para:
To evaluate the POD-like activity and catalytic performance of Fe,S,N/CQDs, we investigated the relationship between the absorbance of the reaction system and time. When keeping the concentration of Fe,S,N/CQDs constant, changing the concentration of TMB resulted in its Michaelis-Menten plot. Furthermore, another Michaelis-Menten plot was obtained by varying the concentration of H2O2. When using TMB as the substrate, 100 μL of H2O2 (1 mM) and 100 μL of TMB (1–20 mM) were added to a centrifuge tube containing 700 μL of HAc-NaAc buffer (0.1 M, pH = 4), and 100 μL of Fe,S,N/CQDs (0.4 mg/mL). When using H2O2 as the substrate, 100 μL of H2O2 (0.2–2 mM) and 100 μL of TMB (18 mM) were added to the mixture of HAc-NaAc buffer and Fe,S,N/CQDs. The absorbance values at 652 nm were monitored after adding the two substrates to the reaction system separately. The absorbance values at 652 nm were monitored after adding the two substrates to the reaction system separately. Based on this, the Michaelis-Menten plots of and Lineweaver-Burk double reciprocal graphs of the two substrates were obtained. Finally, the Michaelis constant (Km
                        ) and maximum initial velocity (Vmax
                        ) were calculated.

Based on the colorimetric sensor constructed using Fe,S,N/CQDs, we investigated the relationship between the concentration of the measured object and the absorbance at 652 nm. As shown in Fig. 4
                        a, a notable observation was that the sensor displayed a proportional increase in the absorbance at 652 nm with the increase in H2O2 concentration. Simultaneously, it can be observed that under normal lighting conditions, the color of the sensor becomes bluer as the concentration of H2O2 increases. Within the concentration range of 1–100 μM, the absorbance values show a good linear relationship with the concentration of H2O2 (Fig. 4b). The linear equation was Y = 0.02071X + 0.1015 (R2 = 0.997), and the limit of detection was calculated as 0.67 μM (3σ/k). Similarly, we investigated the relationship between the concentration of UA and the absorbance values (Fig. 4c–d). Under the circumstance of UA concentrations range from 1-80 μM, this assay for UA provided with a good linear correlations. The calibration equation was expressed as Y = 0.0138X + 0.08952 (R2 = 0.990), and the method showed high sensitivity with a low limit of detection (0.73 μM). We compared the detection performance of this sensor with other methods (Table 2
                        ) [11, 44-49], which indicated that our method exhibits excellent sensitivity and can accurately detect UA.
